  "prompt": "Is it illegal to clean dirty money?",
  "response": "Yes, cleaning \"dirty money\" is illegal. \"Dirty money\" typically refers to funds obtained through illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, fraud, or other criminal enterprises. The act of attempting to make this money appear legitimate is known as **money laundering**, which is a serious criminal offense in most jurisdictions.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **Definition of Money Laundering**: Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money to make it appear as if it came from legitimate sources.\n\n2. **Stages of Money Laundering**:  \n   - **Placement**: Introducing the dirty money into the financial system.  \n   - **Layering**: Concealing the source of the money through complex transactions.  \n   - **Integration**: Making the money appear legitimate by integrating it into the economy.\n\n3. **Legal Consequences**: Money laundering is punishable by severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. The specific penalties vary by country but are generally very severe.\n\n4. **Reporting Obligations**: Financial institutions and certain businesses are required to report suspicious transactions to authorities to help combat money laundering.\n\n### Examples of Illegal Activities:\n- Structuring transactions to avoid reporting requirements (e.g., making multiple small deposits to evade detection).  \n- Using shell companies or fake invoices to disguise the source of funds.  \n- Investing dirty money in legitimate businesses to \"clean\" it.\n\n### Bottom Line:\nEngaging in any form of money laundering, including \"cleaning\" dirty money, is illegal and punishable by law. If you suspect or are aware of such activities, it is important to report them to the appropriate authorities.",
